Furthermore, the electrochemical impedance spectroscopy (EIS) was employed to characterize the interfacial charge transfer properties of the modified electrodes. It can be seen that 0.1wt% MWCNT/Bi4O5Br2 material showed smaller semicircle at high frequencies than that of pure Bi4O5Br2 (Fig. 9
                     ). The smaller semicircle represented the lower electrical resistance. The conjugated π structure of MWCNT enabled that it could work as effective transporters to accelerate the interfacial charge transfer. Moreover, the result of photoluminescence (PL) spectra was in agreement with the above results, with the lower intensity observed for MWCNT/Bi4O5Br2 material, revealing the lower recombination efficiency of photogenerated electron-hole (Fig. 10
                     ). The MWCNT/Bi4O5Br2 with strong-coupling ensured highly efficient electron transfer from the Bi4O5Br2 to the MWCNT and effective spatial separation of the charge carriers can be achieved.
